VIETNAM GAVE Y0U A BROADER VIEW OF HUMAN NATURE -- for better or for worse.  I couldn't have said it better myself.  I think that thought gives me more compassion.<br><br>
Jean Paul Sartre once wrote a short story about a young man in World War II.  He was faced with the dilemma of staying with his ailing mother or becoming &quot;cannon fodder.&quot;  I don't know what he decided.  I will probably go to the library and see if I can find the book.  His choice wasn't easy or so I believe.<br><br>
One of the thoughts I brought back from Vietnam was &quot;nor more pain.&quot;  I wish I had learned earlier how to incorporate that in my life.  My daughter, now seventeen, has had a good life.  I'm glad I didn't have her until I was thirty two..<br><br>
I am proud and embarrassed about some of the &quot;Pauls&quot; I have been, but I do feel this.  I WOULD HAVE NEVER KNOWN HOW IMPORTANT IT WAS TO BE IN VIETNAM HAD I NOT BEEN THERE.<br><br>
GOOD LUCK TO YOU AND THE REST OF YOUR LIFE.<br><br>
